## Before Making Changes — Audit First
- **Always audit the relevant code before making changes.** Read the files, trace the call chain, understand the architecture. Do not blindly edit based on assumptions.
- Check for existing patterns in the codebase and follow them. This is a large monorepo with many apps — each has its own conventions.
- If a bug is reported, verify the root cause before implementing a fix. Prefer minimal upstream fixes over downstream workarounds.

## KeyVault (Secrets / Env Vars)
- **Location:** `C:\cevict-live\scripts\keyvault`
- **Store file:** `C:\Cevict_Vault\env-store.json`
- **Module:** `KeyVault.psm1` — provides `Get-KeyVaultStore`, `Set-KeyVaultSecret`, etc.
- **README:** `C:\cevict-live\scripts\keyvault\README.md` — full command reference
- **App targets config:** `C:\cevict-live\config\keyvault.targets.json` — maps app names to Vercel project IDs
- **Usage:**
  ```powershell
  cd C:\cevict-live\scripts\keyvault
  # Read a secret
  $store = Get-Content 'C:\Cevict_Vault\env-store.json' | ConvertFrom-Json
  $store.secrets.API_SPORTS_KEY

  # Set a secret
  .\set-secret.ps1 -Name KEY_NAME -Value "value"

  # Sync to app .env.local
  .\sync-env.ps1 -AppPath ..\..\apps\progno
  .\sync-env.ps1 -All

  # Push to Vercel (use CLI method, push-vercel.ps1 has API issues)
  .\push-vercel.ps1 -App progno -Env production -DryRun
  ```
- **Do NOT edit `.env.local` files by hand** — they are generated by `sync-env.ps1` from the store. Update the store, then sync.
- When pushing env vars to Vercel via CLI, write values to temp files using `[System.IO.File]::WriteAllText()` to avoid PowerShell `\r\n` corruption.

